During July and August ol this year, there were constant rumours in Oxlord, ol the landing ol the Pretender in Scotland. Amherst in his ‘ Terrae Filius' states that ‘ Captain Owen, a notorious Jacobite‚ and other leading men ol the party were entertained by the heads ol houses ; they walked about the streets with a mob at their heels, huzzaing ‘King James, and the Dulce os Ormond’ and ‘No Usurpers’; Whigs went in iear ol their lives ; portraits ol the Pretender were sold in the town, and H'eame purchased one lor hali-a-guinea3 great number ol students were enlisted; all horses fit ior service were marked; and the notification oi the landing ol the Dulce ol Ormond, was the only thing wanted, before breaking into open warlare’
